<paragraph blockId="10.[820,1459,1742,1958]" lastBlockId="11.[813,1452,1560,1968]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
A single species comprising genetically differentiated allopatric populations, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W.K.H.Peters" authorityYear="1876" box="[1232,1453,1774,1798]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pantodontidae" genus="Pantodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Osteoglossiformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="buchholzi">
<emphasis box="[1232,1453,1774,1798]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Pantodon buchholzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the African butterfly fish, is classified in the family Pantodontidae (
<bibRefCitation author="Nelson" box="[950,1169,1838,1862]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Nelson" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refId="ref25896" refString="Nelson JS, Grande TC, Wilson MVH. Fishes of the world. 5 th ed. Hoboken (NJ): J. Wiley; 2016." type="book" year="2016">
Nelson 
<emphasis box="[1038,1096,1838,1862]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">et al.</emphasis>
, 2016
</bibRefCitation>
), although it is frequently included within the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1831" box="[1129,1290,1870,1894]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Osteoglossidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Osteoglossiformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Osteoglossidae</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis box="[1310,1342,1871,1894]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">e.g</emphasis>
., 
<bibRefCitation author="Taverne" firstAuthor="Taverne" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="1 - 168" refId="ref28048" refString="Taverne L. Osteologie, phylogenese et systematique des teleosteens fossiles et actuels du super ordre des Osteoglossomorphes. Troisieme partie. Evolution des structures osteologiques et conclusions generales relatives a la phylogenese et a la systematique du super ordre. Acad Roy Belg Mem Cl Sci. 1979; 43 (3): 1 - 168. (Collection 8, Serie 2)" type="journal article" year="1979">Taverne, 1979</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Li, Wilson" box="[889,1086,1902,1926]" firstAuthor="Li" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="163 - 174" refId="ref24452" refString="Li G-Q, Wilson MVH. Phylogeny of Osteoglossomorpha. In: Stiassny MLJ, Parenti LR, Johnson GD, editors. Interrelationships of fishes. New York: Academic Press; 1996 a. p. 163 - 174." type="book chapter" year="1996" yearSuffix="a">Li, Wilson, 1996a</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hilton" box="[1098,1239,1902,1927]" firstAuthor="Hilton" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="1 - 100" refId="ref22345" refString="Hilton EJ. Comparative osteology and phylogenetic systematics of fossil and living bony-tongue fishes (Actinopterygii, Teleostei, Osteoglossomorpha). Zool J Linn Soc [serial on the Internet]. 2003; 137 (1): 1 - 100. Available from: https: // doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1096 - 3642.2003.00032. x" type="journal article" year="2003">Hilton, 2003</bibRefCitation>
). This is a relatively small fish, with a strongly upturned mouth, flattened head, short dorsal and anal fins positioned far back on its body, a rounded caudal fin, large wing-like pectoral fins, and pelvic fins with an elongate fin rays (
<figureCitation box="[463,545,1624,1648]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="12.[136,175,1384,1408]" captionTargetBox="[136,1459,854,1368]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[136,1459,851,1371]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Fig. 12. Pantodontidae. Pantodon buchholzi (CU 87447). Scale bar = 2 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3709930" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3709930/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). The head and pectoral fin has a superficial similarity to that of osteoglossines. Despite its similarity in some respects (
<emphasis box="[596,627,1688,1711]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">e.g</emphasis>
., infraorbital bones) to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nelson" authorityYear="1968" box="[238,402,1720,1744]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Osteoglossidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Osteoglossiformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Osteoglossinae">Osteoglossinae</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Nelson" box="[415,614,1720,1744]" firstAuthor="Nelson" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1 - 37" refId="ref25788" refString="Nelson GJ. Infraorbital bones and their bearing on the phylogeny and geography of osteoglosomorph fishes. Am Mus Novit. 1969; 2394: 1 - 37." type="journal article" year="1969">Nelson (1969: 25)</bibRefCitation>
observed that “the systematic position of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1876" baseAuthorityName="Hilton" baseAuthorityYear="2003" box="[431,535,1752,1776]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pantodontidae" genus="Pantodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Osteoglossiformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[431,535,1752,1776]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Pantodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
consequently is obscure.” This remains to be the case (see below). Part of the issue with the systematic placement of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1876" baseAuthorityName="Hilton" baseAuthorityYear="2003" box="[546,650,1816,1840]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pantodontidae" genus="Pantodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Osteoglossiformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[546,650,1816,1840]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Pantodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is that it is a highly derived taxon, with numerous autapomorphies as well as significant character conflict with other osteoglossomorphs. For instance, the absence of a symplectic is shared with Mormyroidea, whereas the absence of an autopalatine is shared with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1831" box="[970,1131,1560,1584]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Osteoglossidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Osteoglossiformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Osteoglossidae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Moritz, Britz" box="[1146,1360,1560,1584]" firstAuthor="Moritz" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1 - 13" refId="ref25164" refString="Moritz T, Britz R. Ontogeny and homology of the basipterygoid articulation in Pantodon buchholzi (Teleostei: Osteoglossomorpha). Zool J Lin Soc [serial on the Internet]. 2005; 144: 1 - 13. Available from: https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2005.00163. x" type="journal article" year="2005">Moritz, Britz, 2005</bibRefCitation>
). However, unlike those of osteoglossid conditions, the scales of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1876" baseAuthorityName="Hilton" baseAuthorityYear="2003" box="[813,917,1624,1648]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pantodontidae" genus="Pantodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Osteoglossiformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[813,917,1624,1648]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Pantodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lack reticulations (
<emphasis box="[1124,1155,1624,1647]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">e.g</emphasis>
., 
<bibRefCitation author="Hilton" box="[1177,1316,1624,1648]" firstAuthor="Hilton" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1 - 100" refId="ref22345" refString="Hilton EJ. Comparative osteology and phylogenetic systematics of fossil and living bony-tongue fishes (Actinopterygii, Teleostei, Osteoglossomorpha). Zool J Linn Soc [serial on the Internet]. 2003; 137 (1): 1 - 100. Available from: https: // doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1096 - 3642.2003.00032. x" type="journal article" year="2003">Hilton, 2003</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 39) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1876" baseAuthorityName="Hilton" baseAuthorityYear="2003" box="[813,917,1656,1680]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pantodontidae" genus="Pantodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Osteoglossiformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[813,917,1656,1680]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Pantodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has two gonads (
<emphasis box="[1103,1171,1656,1679]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">versus</emphasis>
one) (
<bibRefCitation author="Britz" box="[1239,1365,1656,1680]" firstAuthor="Britz" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="209 - 24" refId="ref20175" refString="Britz R. Egg structure and larval development of Pantodon buchholzi (Teleostei: Osteoglossomorpha), with a review of data on reproduction and early life history in other osteoglossomorphs. Ichthyol Explor Freshw. 2004; 15 (3): 209 - 24." type="journal article" year="2004">Britz, 2004</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
